Package software.leonov.common.base

Class CaseInsensitiveEquivalence

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.google.common.base.Equivalence<CharSequence>
      • software.leonov.common.base.CaseInsensitiveEquivalence
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, BiPredicate<CharSequence,​CharSequence>
    public final class CaseInsensitiveEquivalence
extends Equivalence<CharSequence>
implements Serializable
    An Equivalence which determines if two CharSequences are equivalent ignoring case differences.

    This Equivalence can be used to construct a Map which compares its keys in a case-insensitive manner: 

     final Map<String, ...> m = new EquivalenceMap<>(CaseInsensitiveEquivalence.usingDefaultLocale());
    Author:
    Zhenya Leonov

      • doEquivalent

        protected boolean doEquivalent​(CharSequence left,
                               CharSequence right)
        Description copied from class: com.google.common.base.Equivalence
        Implemented by the user to determine whether a and b are considered equivalent, subject to the requirements specified in Equivalence.equivalent(T, T).

        This method should not be called except by Equivalence.equivalent(T, T). When Equivalence.equivalent(T, T) calls this method, a and b are guaranteed to be distinct, non-null instances.
